******
[1] Diarrhea - Iraq (Al-Najaf governorate)
Date: Thu 13 Apr 2017
Source: Arabs Today [in Arabic, trans. Mod.NS, edited]
http://bit.ly/2ofJf4d


The Executive Committee for the Prevention of Cholera in Al-Najaf governorate in Iraq confirmed on [Thu 13 Apr 2017] that no cases of cholera have been recorded in the governorate despite the increased cases of acute diarrhea, which is due to lack of chlorine in the drinking water.

A statement by the Director General of Al-Najaf Health Department, Ali Abdul Zahra, mentioned that an important meeting was held in the department on [Thu 13 Apr 2017] to discuss the causes of recording a number of cases of acute diarrhea in some areas of the governorate. He stressed that the reason is due to the lack of chlorine in the drinking water.

The Director of the Gastroenterology Unit in the Department of Public Health, Abdul Amir Al-Musawi, said in the same statement that laboratory tests confirm that no cases of cholera have been recorded. He indicated that some cases of acute diarrhea have occurred in some areas of the governorate due to the low level of chlorine in the water in these areas. He added that "in summer season, we need to increase the health awareness of the people, with the commitment to add adequate rates of chlorine according to what is determined by the health authorities."

A number of residents of districts and sub-districts in the outskirts of Al-Najaf complained of the poor quality and bad smell of the drinking water in addition to the increased salinity, with the occurrence of many cases of acute diarrhea.

[Byline: Omar Al-Suwaidi]

